<h1 class="main-topic"><a name="deploy_to_heroku">A Quick Guide to Deploying on Heroku</a></h1>
<p class="small-header">
	Contains the commands and simple explanations to deploy on Heroku. For a more in-depth analysis, visit <%= link_to "Heroku's Getting Started with Rails", 'https://devcenter.heroku.com/articles/getting-started-with-rails4', target: '_blank' %>.
</p>

<h4 class="step">
	<a name="add_gems">Step 1: Add two gems for production that enable you to deploy to Heroku smoothly</a>
</h4>
<div class="file-title">Gemfile</div>
<pre><code class="language-ruby">group :development do
	gem 'sqlite3' # if your using sqlite3 database in development
end

group :production do
	gem 'rails_12factor' # for static asset serving and logging
	gem 'pg' # use the PostgreSQL database in production
end</code></pre>

<h4 class="step">
	<a name="initialize_git">Step 2: Initialize a git repository in the root directory of your rails app if you haven't done so yet</a>
</h4>
<pre><code class="language-bash">> git init
> git add .
> git commit -m "commit necessary files for deployment"</code></pre>

<h4 class="step">
	<a name="create_heroku_app">Step 3: Create a git remote called <span class="inline-code">heroku</span> which you can the push your repository to in order deploy your app.</a>
	</h4>
<pre><code class="language-bash">> heroku create
Creating warm-wave-1943... done, stack is cedar-14
http://warm-wave-1943.herokuapp.com/ | git@heroku.com:warm-wave-1943.git
Git remote heroku added</code></pre>

<h4 class="step">
	<a name="push_to_heroku">Step 4: Push your local repository to Heroku</a>
</h4>
<p class="small-header">
<pre><code class="language-bash">> git push heroku master</code></pre>
</p>

<h4 class="step">
	<a name="migrate_db">Step 5: Migrate your database on Heroku</a>
</h4>
<p class="note">
	Note: Whenever you create new migrations locally and push to heroku, you'll have to run those migrations on the production server as well with the command below.
</p>
<pre><code class="language-bash">> heroku run rake db:migrate</code></pre>

<h4 class="step">
	<a name="open_heroku_app">Step 6: Go to the URL of your heroku app from the terminal</a>
</h4>
<pre><code class="language-bash">> heroku open</code></pre>
<p>
If you open your app and see <i>"We're sorry, but something went wrong"</i> type <span class="inline-code">heroku logs</span> to see what your production server is outputting and why it is erroring out.
</p>
<pre><code class="language-bash">> heroku logs</code></pre>



